â”‚                                                              â”‚
â”‚ In Separate F.E/B.E Architecture:                           â”‚
â”‚   Frontend (React/Vue/etc):                                 â”‚
â”‚     âœ… Has state management (useState, state machine, etc)  â”‚
â”‚     âœ… Manages user flow                                    â”‚
â”‚     âœ… Collects data step-by-step                           â”‚
â”‚     âœ… Calls backend when ready                             â”‚
â”‚                                                              â”‚
â”‚   Backend (API):                                            â”‚
â”‚     âœ… ALWAYS stateless                                     â”‚
â”‚     âœ… Just processes requests                              â”‚
â”‚     âœ… No state pattern                                     â”‚
â”‚     âœ… No session management                                â”‚
â”‚                                                              â”‚
â”‚ In Monolithic Architecture (Cheap ATM):                     â”‚
â”‚   State Machine Layer:                                      â”‚
â”‚     âœ… Acts as "frontend"                                   â”‚
â”‚     âœ… Has state pattern                                    â”‚
â”‚     âœ… Manages session                                      â”‚
â”‚                                                              â”‚
â”‚   Services Layer:                                           â”‚
â”‚     âœ… Acts as "backend"                                    â”‚
â”‚     âœ… STILL stateless                                      â”‚
â”‚     âœ… Same as backend API                                  â”‚
â”‚                                                              â”‚
â”‚ The Difference:                                             â”‚
â”‚   In separate F.E/B.E: Frontend is separate software        â”‚
â”‚   In monolithic: "Frontend" is state pattern layer          â”‚
â”‚                                                              â”‚
â”‚   BUT: Backend is ALWAYS stateless in both!                 â”‚
â”‚                                                              â”‚
â””â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”˜

ğŸ”¥ Real-World Examples
Example 1: Amazon (Separate F.E/B.E)
Frontend (React app in browser):
- User browses products
- User adds to cart (frontend state!)
- User enters shipping address (frontend state!)
- User enters payment (frontend state!)
- User clicks "Buy Now"
  â†’ Calls: POST /api/checkout {items, address, payment}

Backend (API):
- Receives ONE request with ALL data
- Processes order
- Returns response
- âŒ NO state management
- âœ… Stateless API

Example 2: Old Vending Machine (Monolithic)
Single Software on Machine:
- State Machine:
  - IdleState â†’ CoinInsertedState â†’ ItemSelectedState â†’ DispensingState
  - Manages flow step-by-step
  - Acts as "frontend"
  
- Services:
  - ValidateCoin()
  - CheckInventory()
  - DispenseItem()
  - Acts as "backend"
  - Stateless!

Why monolithic?
âœ… Cheaper (one computer)
âœ… No network needed
